author.name: Niẓāmī Ganjavī, 1140 or 41-1202 or 3
Ilyās ibn Yūsuf Niẓāmī Ganjavī
الياس بن يوسف نظامي گنجوي
Author dates preferred by cataloger: d. 605 AH / 1209 CE

notesStmt.note: This is an illuminated and illustrated Safavid copy of four of the five poems that comprise the Khamsah (quintet) of Niẓāmī Ganjavī (d. 605 AH / 1209 CE). It does not include Laylá va Majnūn. The text was copied in black nastaʿlīq script by Yādkār the Calligrapher (al-Kātib) in 935 AH / 1529 CE. An illuminated double-page frontispiece opens the codex (fols. 1b-2a), and each poem is introduced with an illuminated headpiece (fols. 33b, 119b, 180b, and 261b). The twenty-seven illustrations appear to have been repainted in India during the twelfth or early thirteenth century AH / eighteenth or early nineteenth CE. The manuscript is bound in late Zand lacquer boards with figural scenes depicting Bahrām Gūr hunting and Khusraw watching Shīrīn bathing. The upper board illustrating Bahrām Gūr is dated 12[0]5 AH / 1790-1 CE.

msContents.textLang: The primary language in this manuscript is Persian.

msItem.title: Khamsah-i Niẓāmī
خمسه نظامي
msItem.incipit: بسم الله الرحمن الرحيم هست كليد در كنج حكيم...
msItem.note: Contains the following four poems: Makhzan al-asrār (fols. 1b-32a); Khusraw va Shīrīn (fols. 33b-118a); Haft paykar (fols. 119b-179a); and Iskandarnāmah (fols. 180b-297a); Layla va Majnūn missing

colophon.note: al-ʿabd al-ḥājjī Yādkār al-Kātib /1/ ghafara dhunūbahu wa-satara /2/ ʿuyūbahu /3/ 903 [sic] /4/
Records scribe's name and date; date appears to be forged

layoutDesc.layout: Framing lines in blue, red, green, gold, and black

handDesc.handNote: Written in nastaʿlīq script in black ink with section headings in red

decoDesc.decoNote: Twenty-seven illustrations; double-page illuminated frontispiece (fols. 1b-2a); four illuminated headpieces (fols. 33b, 119b, 180b, 261b); illuminated borders; framing lines in blue, red, green, gold, and black

decoNote.title: Late Zand lacquer binding
decoNote.note: This late Zand lacquer binding depicts Bahrām Gūr hunting and Fitnah carrying a cow on her shoulders. It is dated 12[0]5 AH / 1790-1 CE. The lacquer boards were made in Iran during the Zand period.

decoNote.title: Double-page illuminated frontispiece
decoNote.note: This is the right side of a double-page illuminated frontispiece inscribed with the title of the first poem of the Khamsah, Makhzan-i asrār.

decoNote.title: Double-page illuminated frontispiece
decoNote.note: This is the left side of a double-page illuminated frontispiece inscribed with the title of the first poem of the Khamsah, Makhzan-i asrār.

decoNote.title: The Prophet Muhammad's ascension
decoNote.note: The Prophet Muhammad is depicted on Buraq, led by the angel Gabriel ascending to the heavens.

decoNote.title: Nūshirvān and his prime minster Dastūr
decoNote.note: Riding through a ruined village, the Sasanian Nūshirvān and his prime minster Dastūr see two owls talking.

decoNote.title: An old woman implores Sultan Sanjar for help
decoNote.note: An old woman approaches the throne of Sultan Sanjar to recount her oppression.

decoNote.title: An old man brought before a tyrant
An old woman speaking with a confidant of King Jamshīd
decoNote.note: At a court gathering, an old woman speaks with a confidant of King Jamshīd.

decoNote.title: Incipit with illuminated headpiece
decoNote.note: This incipit page has an illuminated headpiece; it begins the second poem of the Khamsah, Khusraw va Shīrīn.

Shāhpūr visiting Shīrīn
decoNote.note: Shāhpūr is shown before the Armenian princess Shīrīn at a court gathering.

Late Zand lacquer binding
decoNote.note: This late Zand lacquer binding depicts Khusraw watching Shīrīn bathing. It was made in Iran during the Zand period. (The upper board is dated 12[0]5 AH / 1790-1 CE.)

binding.p: Dates to the twelfth century AH / eighteenth CE; late Zand lacquer binding (without flap); upper board depicts Bahrām Gūr hunting and Fitnah carrying a cow on her shoulders, dated 12[0]5 AH / 1790-1 CE; lower board depicts Khusraw watching Shīrīn bathing; red leather doublures have gold-painted decoration
